<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">28249351</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2017</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>09</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2017</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>09</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1097-4598</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>56</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2017</Year><Month>Oct</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Muscle &amp; nerve</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Muscle Nerve</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Cross-education after high-frequency versus low-frequency volume-matched handgrip training.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>689</StartPage><EndPage>695</EndPage><MedlinePgn>689-695</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1002/mus.25637</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Cross-education training programs cause interlimb asymmetry of strength and hypertrophy. We examined the cross-education effects from a high-frequency (HF) versus a low-frequency (LF) volume-matched handgrip training program on interlimb asymmetry.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Right-handed participants completed either HF (n = 10; 2 &#xd7; 6 repetitions 10 times per week) or LF (n = 9; 5 &#xd7; 8 repetitions 3 times per week) training. Testing occurred twice before and once after 4 weeks of right-handed isometric handgrip training totaling 120 weekly repetitions. Measures were maximal isometric handgrip and wrist flexion torque, muscle thickness, and muscle activation (electromyography; EMG).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Grip strength was greater in both limbs posttraining, pooled across groups (P &lt; 0.001). Trained limb muscle thickness increased in both groups (P &lt; 0.05; untrained, P = 0.897). EMG and wrist flexion torque did not change (all P &gt; 0.103).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DISCUSSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Both LF and HF induced cross-education of grip strength to the untrained limb, but HF did not reduce asymmetry. These findings have implications for injury rehabilitation. Muscle Nerve 56: 689-695, 2017.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2017 Wiley Periodicals, Inc.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Boyes</LastName><ForeName>Natasha G</ForeName><Initials>NG</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Kinesiology, University of Saskatchewan, 87 Campus Drive, Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, Canada, S7N 5B2.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Yee</LastName><ForeName>Peter</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Kinesiology, University of Saskatchewan, 87 Campus Drive, Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, Canada, S7N 5B2.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lanovaz</LastName><ForeName>Joel L</ForeName><Initials>JL</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Kinesiology, University of Saskatchewan, 87 Campus Drive, Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, Canada, S7N 5B2.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Farthing</LastName><ForeName>Jonathan P</ForeName><Initials>JP</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Kinesiology, University of Saskatchewan, 87 Campus Drive, Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, Canada, S7N 5B2.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D003160">Comparative Study</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2017</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>05</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Muscle Nerve</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>7803146</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0148-639X</ISSNLink